    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1917-09-05T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1917-09-05T00:00:00-05:00" n="528"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d528">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 195/102</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Assistant Secretary of State</hi> (<persName
                        corresp="#p_PW1" type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Phillips</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to President <persName corresp="#p_WW1" type="to"
                            >Wilson</persName>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1917-09-05">
                            <hi rend="italic">September 5, 1917</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">My Dear Mr. President</hi>: I had a talk this morning with
                    Mr. <persName>Gillet</persName>, who is one of Mr. <persName corresp="#p_TA1"
                        >Tardieu</persName>’s right-hand men, and explained fully your anxiety to
                    help France in every possible way, that you were in close touch with the
                    Shipping Board on the subject of Mr. <persName corresp="#p_TA1"
                        >Tardieu</persName>’s memorandum,<note n="1" xml:id="d528fn1">
                        <hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_617">p. 617</ref>.</note> and
                    that I felt that there was nothing to be gained at the present moment by a
                    further conference between you and Mr. <persName corresp="#p_TA1"
                        >Tardieu</persName>. I am sure that Mr. <persName corresp="#p_TA1"
                        >Tardieu</persName> will fully understand your position and will not urge
                    for an interview at this time.</p>
                <p>Mr. <persName>Gillet</persName> said that their real anxiety was for a decision
                    on our part; that if there was a decision in the negative it would at least put
                    them in a position to proceed on their own account. He expressed Mr. <persName
                        corresp="#p_TA1">Tardieu</persName>’s fear that there would be no decision
                    one way or the other, and that this would give rise to a very embarrassing
                    position for France in view of the extreme urgency for additional shipping.</p>
                <p>With assurances of respect [etc.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_PW1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">William Phillips</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
